    <!--         SECTION ONE: SYMMETRY & TRANSFORMATIONS                 -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_12">• A transformation moves every point to form a new figure.
\n • Central symmetry reflects points across a center.
\n • Axial symmetry reflects across a line; homothety scales from a center.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does axial symmetry reflect a figure across a line? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefQuestion_12">Does axial symmetry reflect a figure across a line?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerOne_12">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerTwo_12">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerThree_12"></string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_12">True</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_12">• Circles and parallelograms have centers of symmetry.
\n • Shapes like triangles and squares have specific symmetry axes.
\n • Homothetic figures share the same shape and center.</string>

    <!-- Q: How many axes of symmetry does a square have? Answer: 4 -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsQuestion_12">How many axes of symmetry does a square have?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerOne_12">2</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_12">4</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerThree_12">1</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_12">4</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExamples_12">• To find point M on line p minimising AM+MB: reflect B across p to get B′. The straight line AB′ crosses p at M — this gives the shortest total path by the triangle inequality.
\n • Any other point N on p satisfies AN+NB = AN+NB′ &gt; AB′ = AM+MB′ = AM+MB, confirming M is the minimum.
\n • This reflection technique is the standard construction for the shortest-path-via-a-line problem and is a direct application of axial symmetry.</string>

    <!-- Q: To minimise AM+MB with M on line p, which point is reflected across p? Answer: B -->
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExQuestion_12">To find the point M on line p that minimises AM+MB, which point is reflected across p?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_12">M</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_12">A</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_12">B</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_12">B</string>

