    <!--                   SECTION THREE: SIMILITUDE                     -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDef_12">• A similitude scales distances by a constant ratio k.
\n • Figures are similar if one maps to the other by such a transformation.
\n • Homothety is a special case of similitude.</string>

    <!-- Q: Is homothety a special case of similitude? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefQuestion_12">Is homothety a special case of similitude?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerOne_12">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerTwo_12">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerThree_12"></string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_12">True</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryProperties_12">• Similitude keeps lines straight and angles equal.
\n • Preserves order of points along a line.
\n • Homothety is always a type of similitude.</string>

    <!-- Q: Does a similitude preserve angles? Answer: True -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsQuestion_12">Does a similitude transformation preserve angles?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerOne_12">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_12">False</string>
    <!-- Only 2 answers for True/False — third answer intentionally removed -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerThree_12"></string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_12">True</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExamples_12">• Homothety with center O and ratio k = 3 maps every point M to M′ where OM′ = 3×OM. The image triangle M′O′N′ is similar to MON with ratio 3, proven by comparing sides: M′N′/MN = OM′/OM = 3.
\n • Since M′N′ = k×MN for every pair of image points, all distances are scaled by k — confirming homothety is a similitude.
\n • A similitude with k = 1 is a motion (isometry); any k ≠ 1 produces a strictly similar but non-congruent image, illustrating the relationship between motions and similitudes.</string>

    <!-- Q: A homothety with ratio k=3 multiplies all distances by what factor? Answer: 3 -->
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExQuestion_12">A homothety with ratio k = 3 multiplies all distances by what factor?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_12">9</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_12">1/3</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_12">3</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_12">3</string>

